0-5_p005_882c4e9e,inscribed object,plaque,marble,none,Unclassified,unknown,0-5.pdf,5,"Plaque, marble. Rectangular polished marble plaque with a base of the same stone, bearing five letters: ""A click and HBL"""" and the inscription """"Horn A and Miledi - Southern Arabian Peninsula (old Yemen)."""" Height 36 cm.""","Stela, alabaster. South Arabian aniconic stela of slightly trapezoidal form, rounded at the top, with a rectangular plinth engraved with the owner's name. The object measures 41.5 cm in height and 24 cm in width. According to the source text, such stelae were placed in a niche or against a wall.",https://www.pba-auctions.com/lot/7974/1617601?refurl=Stèle,pba-auctions.com,98,0.293524,0,0.146762,score_txt only,pba-auctions.com,Unknown,USA,auction
31- _31_p026_d235d123,inscribed object,tablet,bronze,none,Unclassified,unknown,31- _31.pdf,26,"Tablet, bronze, with an inscription and window holes distributed on three angles for stabilization. The engraved text records a vow made by a person named Saad El for the Abed, who was tried at Shebhan's temple, invoking the gods Athtar, uncle, and prophet the vow was made on his behalf and on behalf of his brother and his son. Dimensions recorded as 31.5 x 26.6 cm.","Votive plaque, stone, inscribed with eight lines in Qatabanite characters. The inscription records a dedication by Sa'adil of the clan of Ab'am to Hawkam Nabat. The proper names in this dedication are already known from other Qatabanite inscriptions. Palaeographically, the monument appears to be close to periods C and D of A. Petite lacune at the lower left corner otherwise in very good condition. The deity Hawkam is identified in the source as a goddess. Height 31.5 cm width 26.6 cm.",https://www.pba-auctions.com/lot/4963/1205126-grande-plaque-votive-inscrite-de-huit-lignes-en-caracteres,pba-auctions.com,125,0.454516,0.0868217,0.270669,combined score,pba-auctions.com,Unknown,USA,auction
0-21_p016_7c432e20,inscribed object,plaque,marble,none,Unclassified,unknown,0-21.pdf,16,"Mural, marble stone, irregular plaque form, depicting a seated figure on a chair with the left hand raised and the right hand extended backward beneath the figure is an inscription in a single line on the baseline reading ""hj and t/t mr n."""" Dimensions: 22.5 Ã— 14.5 Ã— 4 cm (8 7/8 Ã— 5 11/16 Ã— 1 9/16 in.). Dated to the second century BC.""","Stela, calcite-alabaster, South Arabian, 2nd-1st century BCE. The object depicts a woman seated on a folding stool with a cushioned seat. An inscription is present, transliterated as Hywt /Dmrn. The material is identified as calcite-alabaster from South Arabia.",https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76487/stela-with-a-seated-woman/,art.thewalters.org,159,0.386609,0.0895967,0.238103,combined score,thewalters.org,Baltimore,USA,museum
0-14_p043_1add3b82,inscribed object,tablet,bronze,none,Unclassified,unknown,0-14.pdf,43,"Rectangular tablet, bronze, with an engraved inscription in 12 lines. Metal: bronze. Dimensions: 23.5 Ã— 15.7 cm. First century AD. The tablet has holes in the four corners and is described as in very good condition.","Plaque, bronze. South Arabian bronze inscriptional plaque preserving twelve lines of inscription in raised relief. The text records that Yin'am, his brother, and their sons the Banu Rasham dedicated the plaque to their god LBNH, bull of M'RBN, in his sanctuary at Sim'ân, as an inscription of divine ordinance ordered for them in his property, for their wellbeing and the wellbeing of all that he has acquired and will acquire, and for the removal of evil, wrong, ill-will, injustice, WTRKS, and 'W/'F of an enemy both far and near. Circa 1st century A.D. Dimensions: 23.5 cm high, 15.7 cm wide.",https://www.lot-art.com/auction-lots/A-South-Arabian-bronze-inscriptional-plaque/255-south_arabian-06.7.23-bonham,lot-art.com,237,0.380228,0.0679975,0.224113,combined score,lot-art.com,Amsterdam,Netherlands,platform
