0-5_p009_16162ad0,jewelry,ring,unknown,none,Unclassified,unknown,0-5.pdf,9,"Metal artifact, metal, rectangular conglomerate on four legs, with edges decorated with geometric shapes the sides are covered with a walrus-enveloped decorator and a restaurant with prominent animal head feces, and the inter-lettered emptiness includes various plant decorative elements.","Brazier, brass, second half 13th century. Probably made in Egypt. This portable brazier was used as a grill and heater. It has lion-headed knobs with rings that served as receptacles for handles to transport the heated unit, and confronted dragon heads on each side that functioned as spit brackets. The monumental inscription names and honors the patron, identified as the second ruler of the Rasulid dynasty, al-Malik al-Muzaffar Shams al-Din Yusuf ibn 'Umar (r. 1250–95). His dynastic emblem, a five-petalled rosette on a circular shield, appears prominently on both sides of each corner bracket.",https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/444540,metmuseum.org,105,0.478373,0.127682,0.303028,combined score,metmuseum.org,New York,USA,museum
