0-21_p026_e8ab5e07,jewelry,ring,iron,human,Late Antiquity,5th century,0-21.pdf,26,"Necklace, iron, in the form of a human head wearing a turban, with a master maker above the necklace and a hole in the upper part. 1st to 5th century AD. Dimensions: 2 11/16 x 1 9/16 x 1 in. (6.8 x 4 x 2.5 cm).","Pendant with human face, iron, South Arabian, 1st-5th century CE. The object is an oval plaque depicting a male head with an elaborate headdress resembling the Macedonian kausia, a flat hat. The pendant is dated broadly to the 1st-5th century CE and is attributed to South Arabia. Similar pendants were made in the Roman Empire, but it is not possible to determine from the source whether this example reached South Arabia as an import or was made locally after a foreign model. The recorded dimensions are 6.8 x 4 x 2.5 cm.",https://art.thewalters.org/detail/76495/pendant-with-human-face/,art.thewalters.org,161,0.368094,0.0965813,0.232338,combined score,thewalters.org,Baltimore,USA,museum
