0-4_p003_16facb8e,sculpture,statue,marble,lion,Unclassified,unknown,0-4.pdf,3,"Statue, marble stone. Woman's statue depicting a seated female figure on a chair of the same material. The figure is described as clear-cut, with a low-cut garment, thinning form, and cuffed sleeves the surface is noted as hairy. The object is associated with Barkat House and is recorded as missing. Photo number 6.","Sabaean seated statuette of a woman, calcite-alabaster, dated 600 BCE–100 BCE, height 20.3 cm. The female figure is seated and wears a long dress her hands are held before her. The ears and arms are pierced, and the lower arms project horizontally forward at right angles to the upper arms, a gesture described as common in this type of statuary. The object is identified as Sabaean, with the text noting a probable southern provenance and mentioning that similar early examples have been unearthed from Main, while alabaster was widespread in Qataban.",https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/60216-sabaean-seated-statuette-of-a-woman-600-bce-100-bce/,barakatgallery.com,178,0.316648,0,0.158324,score_txt only,barakatgallery.com,London,UK,dealer
0-4_p008_edea912b,sculpture,statue,stone,none,Unclassified,unknown,0-4.pdf,8,"Statue, granite stone, described as a statue in granite stone with a pale white surface and red state the source text also mentions cheek, eyes, and a global auction in Britain, but the description is otherwise unclear and fragmentary.","Sabean head of a woman, granite, dated 600 BCE–100 BCE. The object measures 24.1 x 10.8 cm (9 1/2 x 4 1/4 in). It is described as an architectural fragment from a notable public or ceremonial building in the ancient kingdom of Saba, centered in modern-day Yemen. The piece is identified as a striking head and is noted for breaks to the top, side, and base, suggesting an architectural origin. The source states that it may have served as a caryatid for a structure of social importance. The Sabeans are described as being known for stone works, including alabaster and granite, and for a distinctive sculptural style shaped by religious and cultural contacts.",https://barakatgallery.eu/artworks/54706-sabean-granite-head-of-a-woman-600-bce-100-bce/,barakatgallery.com,180,0.39377,0,0.196885,score_txt only,barakatgallery.com,London,UK,dealer
