0-30_p010_82b6e20a,sculpture,statue,marble,human,Unclassified,unknown,0-30.pdf,10,"Human statue, marble, Late 2000 B.C.E. Height 37.6 cm, width 11.5 cm, depth 10.7 cm.","Standing male figure, alabaster (calcite), ca. late 1st millennium BCE. This funerary or votive object was intended for placement in a tomb or temple. The figure stands frontally and wears a long, plain garment reaching almost to the ankles. It is carved in one piece with a base that bears the name of the individual and his clan, Sadiqim Ma'ad. The eyes and eyebrows are carved to receive inlays, now missing. The arms are bent at the elbows and extend outward at right angles to the body one hand is clenched in a fist and pierced vertically to hold an object, perhaps a scepter, now lost, while the other hand is open. The undersurface of the base and the top and back of the head are roughly carved, consistent with statues that were set in niches and left unfinished on non-visible surfaces. The ears are placed high on the head, and the aquiline nose, small mouth, and fully frontal pose are characteristic of human images made in southwestern Arabia.",https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/326695,metmuseum.org,189,0.294657,0.0230799,0.158869,combined score,metmuseum.org,New York,USA,museum
